



| Directory   | Description                                                 | Important Files / Examples                                                                             |
| ----------- | ----------------------------------------------------------- | ------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------ |
| /           | Root directory â€” top of the file system hierarchy.          | Contains all other directories.                                                                        |
| /bin        | Essential user command binaries.                            | `ls`, `cp`, `mv`, `rm`, `cat`, `echo`, `grep`                                                          |
| /boot       | Boot loader files and Linux kernel.                         | `vmlinuz`, `initrd.img`, `/boot/grub/grub.cfg`                                                         |
| /dev        | Device files that represent hardware.                       | `/dev/sda` (hard disk), `/dev/tty` (terminal), `/dev/null`                                             |
| /etc        | System configuration files.                                 | `passwd`, `group`, `shadow`, `fstab`, `hostname`, `hosts`, `resolv.conf`, `sudoers`, `ssh/sshd_config` |
| /home       | Home directories for all normal users.                      | `/home/user1`, `/home/user2`                                                                           |
| /lib        | Shared libraries required by `/bin` and `/sbin` binaries.   | `libc.so`, `ld-linux.so`                                                                               |
| /lib64      | 64-bit shared libraries (on 64-bit systems).                | System dynamic linker files.                                                                           |
| /media      | Mount point for removable media.                            | `/media/usb`, `/media/cdrom`                                                                           |
| /mnt        | Temporary mount point for external drives.                  | `/mnt/data`, `/mnt/test`                                                                               |
| /opt        | Optional or third-party software packages.                  | `/opt/google/chrome`, `/opt/tomcat`                                                                    |
| /proc       | Virtual filesystem providing process and kernel info.       | `/proc/cpuinfo`, `/proc/meminfo`, `/proc/[PID]/status`                                                 |
| /root       | Home directory for the **root (superuser)** account.        | Root user's personal files and configs.                                                                |
| /run        | Runtime information for system processes.                   | `/run/utmp`, `/run/systemd/`                                                                           |
| /sbin       | System administration binaries (for root).                  | `ifconfig`, `fdisk`, `reboot`, `mount`, `shutdown`                                                     |
| /srv        | Data for system services.                                   | `/srv/www` (web server), `/srv/ftp`                                                                    |
| /sys        | Virtual filesystem showing kernel and hardware details.     | `/sys/class/net`, `/sys/block`                                                                         |
| /tmp        | Temporary files created by programs.                        | `/tmp/test.txt`, deleted on reboot.                                                                    |
| /usr        | Secondary hierarchy for user programs, libraries, and docs. | `/usr/bin`, `/usr/lib`, `/usr/share`, `/usr/local`                                                     |
| /var        | Variable data â€” logs, cache, spool files.                   | `/var/log/syslog`, `/var/mail`, `/var/cache`, `/var/spool`, `/var/www/html`                            |
| /lost+found | Used to recover files after unexpected shutdowns.           | Auto-created by file system tools.                                                                     |

